  "text": "The Rust compiler's type inference engine is centered around three core structures:\n\n1. **InferCtxt** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/mod.rs:231): The main inference context struct that manages all type inference operations in the compiler. It holds the TyCtxt (typing context), tracks typing mode, manages region constraints, and handles type variable resolution. This is the fundamental data structure that orchestrates type inference across the entire compilation process.\n\n2. **FnCtxt** (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/fn_ctxt/mod.rs:44): The function-level type checker that specializes InferCtxt for checking individual functions. It extends the inference capabilities with function-specific state including body context, parameter environment, return type coercion tracking, and coroutine type information. FnCtxt is used during HIR (High-level Intermediate Representation) typechecking to infer types within function bodies.\n\n3. **TypeVariableOrigin** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/type_variable.rs:94): A metadata structure that tracks how type variables are created and originated. It stores the span where the type variable was introduced and an optional DefId of the type parameter it was instantiated for. This is used for diagnostic purposes and helps the compiler report meaningful error messages when type inference fails.\n\nThese three components work together: InferCtxt provides the core inference machinery, FnCtxt specializes it for function-level checking, and TypeVariableOrigin tracks the provenance of inferred type variables throughout the process."
}

